  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting cash transactions above certain thresholds\n- Documenting and reporting potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing comprehensive AML programs\n- Conducting regular internal audits\n- Training employees on AML procedures\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Identifying high-risk customers and transactions\n- Implementing enhanced monitoring for potential money laundering\n\n5. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Preserving documentation for specified periods\n- Providing information to regulatory authorities when requested\n\n6. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Potential significant financial penalties\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of operating licenses\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent financial crimes and ensure transparent financial systems.",
